1Ô∏è‚É£ Physical Layer (L1)
- Role: Transmits raw bits (electrical/optical)
- Protocols: Ethernet, Fiber, Wi-Fi
- Use: GCP Interconnect, Data center cabling, CDN edge latency

2Ô∏è‚É£ Data Link Layer (L2)
- Role: Node-to-node data transfer (MAC)
- Protocols: Ethernet, ARP, VLAN
- Use: VPC interfaces, Hybrid networking (VLAN tagging)

3Ô∏è‚É£ Network Layer (L3)
- Role: Routing packets across networks
- Protocols: IP, ICMP, BGP
- Use: VPC routing, Cloud Router (BGP), ICMP (ping/debug)

4Ô∏è‚É£ Transport Layer (L4)
- Role: Reliable delivery, ports, sessions
- Protocols: TCP (reliable), UDP (fast), QUIC (HTTP/3)
- Use: APIs (TCP), DNS/VoIP (UDP), Mobile web (QUIC)

5Ô∏è‚É£ Session Layer (L5)
- Role: Session control, handshake
- Protocols: TLS, gRPC
- Use: TLS termination at LB, secure RPC between services

6Ô∏è‚É£ Presentation Layer (L6)
- Role: Data format, encryption, compression
- Protocols: JSON, Protobuf, TLS, GZIP
- Use: REST/gRPC payloads, secure APIs, bandwidth savings

7Ô∏è‚É£ Application Layer (L7)
- Role: Application-level protocols
- Protocols: HTTP(S), WebSocket, DNS, SMTP, gRPC, MQTT
- Use: Web apps (HTTP), Real-time chat (WebSocket), IoT (MQTT), API gateways (gRPC)

‚úÖ GCP Examples:
- L3: Cloud Router with BGP
- L4: TCP LB or QUIC via HTTP/3
- L7: Cloud Run with gRPC, Cloud Functions (HTTPS)
- L2-L3: Partner Interconnect with VLANs & BGP

üìù Tip: Choose protocols by latency, reliability, and security trade-offs.

